\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This policy normalizes seven (7) distinct upstream intake paths into a single,
 consistent handling framework;
 maintains the canonical Indicator of Compromise (IoC) list that governs incident declaration throughout the manual;
 and establishes the CJIS-compliant reporting mechanics and incident record structure required for operational execution and audit accountability.
 This policy is activated immediately upon potential cybersecurity incident discovery and governs all activity through declaration and handoff to the appropriate operational response policies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Indicator of Compromise List Architecture
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This policy maintains the canonical IoC list that governs cybersecurity incident declaration across the ECIO Policy Manual.
 The list uses a two-layer architecture separating permanent categorical triggers from current technical indicators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Layer 1 —
 Categorical Triggers:
\series default

 Layer 1 consists of six (6) permanent,
 technology-agnostic categories that constitute an IoC regardless of how they manifest technically.
 Layer 1 categories reside in this policy text.
 The IT Director shall not approve changes to Layer 1 categories or definitions unless the fundamental nature of cybersecurity threats changes.
 The IT Director shall document any change to a Layer 1 category or its definition as a policy amendment.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Category A —
 Unauthorized Access or Access Anomaly:
\series default

 Any confirmed or strongly suspected access to systems,
 data,
 or accounts by an unauthorized party,
 or any access by an authorized party outside their defined scope.
 Includes credential compromise,
 privilege escalation,
 lateral movement,
 and account takeover.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Category B —
 Malicious Code Activity:
\series default

 Presence or execution of malware,
 ransomware,
 spyware,
 rootkits,
 trojans,
 worms,
 or any software not authorized under the ECIO software management framework that exhibits destructive,
 exfiltration,
 or command-and-control behavior.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Category C —
 Denial of Service:
\series default

 Any attack that impairs the availability of County IT systems or services through resource exhaustion,
 flooding,
 or disruption,
 whether targeted at ECIO infrastructure or originating from ECIO infrastructure against external targets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Category D —
 Data Compromise or Exfiltration:
\series default

 Any confirmed or suspected unauthorized access to,
 disclosure of,
 modification of,
 or exfiltration of County data,
 with particular emphasis on CJI,
 PII,
 and systems classified as Tier 1 or Tier 2 under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Recovery Operations and Restoration Prioritization).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Category E —
 Targeted Reconnaissance:
\series default

 Systematic probing,
 scanning,
 or enumeration of ECIO infrastructure that demonstrates specific targeting of internal systems,
 knowledge of internal topology or naming conventions not publicly available,
 or that is combined with any follow-on access attempt,
 credential probe,
 or lateral movement indicator.
 Undifferentiated broad-sweep scanning of external-facing IP space does not constitute an IoC under this category absent one of the preceding qualifying conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Category F —
 Improper Use with Security Nexus:
\series default

 Acceptable use violations,
 insider activity,
 or policy violations that involve attempted or confirmed unauthorized access to data,
 systems,
 or accounts beyond the violator's authorized scope.
 Routine acceptable use violations without a security nexus remain within the governance of 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Layer 2 —
 Specific Indicators:
\series default

 Layer 2 consists of current,
 actionable technical signatures —
 including file hashes,
 IP ranges,
 behavioral patterns,
 known malware identifiers,
 and credential stuffing signatures —
 maintained as a governed artifact in the System of Engagement.
 Layer 2 reflects the evolving threat landscape and shall be updated as that landscape changes.
 The Assistant IT Director owns routine Layer 2 maintenance under standing authority.
 Routine maintenance includes adding new indicators and removing stale ones.
 The IT Director shall be notified of each update.
 The Assistant IT Director shall source Layer 2 indicators from recognized threat intelligence sources and internal postmortem findings.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Constraint:
\series default

 No fixed source list shall be mandated;
 source selection is at the discretion of the Assistant IT Director.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
IoC List Review:
\series default

 The Assistant IT Director shall review the IoC list as a whole no less than quarterly.
 The quarterly cadence is a floor,
 not a ceiling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
False Positive Disposition:
\series default

 When a declared incident is determined to be a false positive,
 the Incident Commander shall flag the triggering indicator in the work order notes at the time of that determination.
 The indicator shall not be modified at the time of disposition.
 A standalone thirty (30) day review window shall be initiated at the time of false positive determination.
 Indicator modification requires a deliberate review cycle conducted within that thirty (30) day window,
 not an in-the-moment decision at disposition.
\end_layout

