\series default
,
 Section 6.1 —
 High,
 Medium,
 or Low —
 and answers how serious the incident is.
 Chapter 4 severity classification is independent of and non-interacting with the five-tier operational severity framework established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Service Catalog and SLA Policy).
 The Incident Commander may reclassify severity at any point and shall document any reclassification in the work order Notes with the basis for the change.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 CJIS Notification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
CJIS Security Policy v6.0,
 Section IR-6 establishes a two-part notification obligation.
 Both parts apply to all declared incidents and shall be executed and documented in the Chapter 4 checklist CJIS notification log.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Part (a) —
 Internal Reporting:
\series default

 All Information Operations Personnel shall report any suspected or confirmed security incident to the Incident Commander immediately upon discovery,
 not to exceed one (1) hour after discovery.
 Work order creation constitutes the formal internal report satisfying Part (a).
 The work order creation timestamp in the System of Engagement is the documented record of internal report completion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Part (b) —
 External Notification:
\series default

 Upon declaration,
 the IT Director acting in the role of LASO shall notify the CSO,
 the SIB Chief,
 or the Interface Agency Official where CJI involvement is confirmed or cannot be ruled out at triage.
 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Communication Protocols and Partner Integration) governs the execution of external notification.
 This policy owns the obligation trigger and the CJIS notification log entry documenting that handoff.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
One-Hour Clock:
\series default

 The one (1) hour Part (a) clock starts at the first documented action in the System of Engagement:
 the work order creation timestamp for State 2 intake events,
 and the IoC observation notation timestamp for State 1 events.
 If prior awareness is established through a channel outside of the System of Engagement before the work order is created,
 that earlier time shall be noted in the work order and becomes the operative clock start for Part (a).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
CJI Involvement Determination:
\series default

 CJIS Part (b) external notification attaches only to declared incidents where CJI involvement is confirmed or cannot be ruled out at triage.
 The IT Director or the Assistant IT Director shall record a CJI involvement determination —
 confirmed,
 possible,
 or ruled out with its basis —
 in the Chapter 4 checklist for every declared incident,
 regardless of whether Part (b) is ultimately triggered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Notification Windows:
\series default

 All notification windows are measured in continuous calendar hours.
 No business-hours qualification applies,
 and no after-hours exception applies.
 For declared incidents with a CJI nexus,
 the IT Director shall initiate the handoff to 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 for external notification within the following windows measured from the time of declaration:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
High severity with CJI nexus
\series default
:
 not to exceed one (1) hour from declaration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Medium severity with CJI nexus
\series default
:
 not to exceed four (4) hours from declaration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Low severity with CJI nexus
\series default
:
 not to exceed twenty-four (24) hours from declaration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.7 Evidence Artifact Retention
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Incident Record Retention:
\series default

 The incident record —
 comprising the work order,
 Chapter 4 checklist,
 Notes,
 and system-generated audit trail —
 shall be retained for three (3) calendar years from the end of the calendar year of incident closure,
 in accordance with LRDA 20071728 (IT Access Control Reviews and Audit Trails).
 This retention period exceeds the CJIS AU-11 one-year minimum for audit records.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Evidence Artifact Retention:
\series default

 Evidence artifacts —
 including camera footage segments,
 exported logs,
 forensic captures,
 and file attachments in the work order —
 constitute security activity records and incident reports under LRDA 20071279 (Property Management:
 Security Records) and shall be retained for three (3) calendar years from the end of the calendar year to which they pertain,
 subject to the path-specific conditions below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Path 1 —
 Confirmed incident,
 law enforcement involved:
\series default

 The IT Director shall turn over evidence artifacts to law enforcement.
 ECIO shall retain documentation of the transfer —
 identifying what was transferred,
 to whom,
 when,
 and under what authority —
 for three (3) calendar years from the end of the calendar year of custody transfer.
 Evidence artifacts are released from ECIO retention upon documented custody transfer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Path 2 —
 Confirmed incident,
 no law enforcement involvement:
\series default

 The IT Director shall ensure evidence artifacts are retained for three (3) calendar years from the end of the calendar year to which the incident pertains,
 in accordance with LRDA 20071279,
 or for the duration of any related audit or legal hold,
 whichever is longer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Path 3 —
 False positive disposition:
\series default

 The IT Director shall ensure evidence artifacts are retained for three (3) calendar years from the end of the calendar year of the false positive determination,
 in accordance with LRDA 20071279,
 or for the duration of any related audit or legal hold,
 whichever is longer.
 The thirty (30) day indicator review window established in Section 6.1 governs modification of the triggering IoC indicator and is independent of this retention obligation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Path 4 —
 CJI-involved incidents:
\series default

 Standard tiered retention as described in Paths 1 through 3 applies.
 The IT Director shall conduct a due-diligence review for any applicable CJIS-specific retention requirement before disposition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All retention obligations under this section are subject to legal hold requirements,
 litigation preservation obligations,
 and NRS 239.125.
 In the event of a conflict between this section and a legal hold or litigation preservation obligation,
 the legal hold or litigation preservation obligation governs.
\end_layout

